			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Does anyone feel like being a bard is cheating?<a name="27119"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 12 04 1:22 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Ravenous I am new to this board and don't want to be a problem so I will not flame you (though I was sorely tempted to do so when reading your post)
<br />

<br />
I take offense to your comments about the other classes specifically the cleric and chanter comments.  A good cleric knows that mana management sometimes involves rooting mobs that are on the casters, stunning mobs that are on the chanter and even putting that mace to good use from time to time.  It's not always about medding, healing and buffing.  It's about how to manage your mana vs the health of the group.
<br />

<br />
The busiest I've ever been has been while playing a chanter in a mediocre group in highkeep.  I've leveled a bard and 2 chanters there (plus a few other characters not related to this post).  There was a night when the group was losing control of the War room over and over again before my chanter joined, then 6 hours with only 1 death, then I leave and they lose the room again before I am done buying food/water and doing my banking.  That particular night we had 2 different bards work their way through the group.  While the first one was awful, the other was a good bard to group with.  I even stayed behind after leaving the group to help them maintain control of the last room pop while my replacement (another chanter actually) got acclimated to the group.  There's no &quot;I&quot; in group.  Bards are a great asset to any group but don't dis the other classes that help make that grop possible.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
